{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_cicerone_ver01/data/sn83016244/00271761302/1937100801/0329.xml":{"full_text":"Associated Press Day Wire\nService.\nFor 57 Years Devoted to the\nBest Interests of Key West\nVOLUME LVIII. No. 239.\nCelebration Of \u201cEl Grito\nDe Yara\u201d In Key West\nStarts Tomorrow Morning\nFestivities Of Event To\nBegin With Arrival Of\nGunboat With Delegation\nFrom Havana\nAnnouncement of the official\nprogram which will mark the cele\nbration of \u201cEl Grito de Yara\u201d in\nKey West, beginning tomorrow\nand concluding Monday, was made\nyesterday by the officers of San\nCarlos Institute.\nTomorrow morning about 8\no'clock the Cuban Gunboat Cuba\nwill arrive at one of the finger\npiers at the naval station subma\nrine base, and plans have been\n\ncompleted for giving the ship and\narrivals a rousing reception.\nSunday morning at S :30 o\u2019clock,\neremonie s attendant upon placing\nthe cornerstone of the institution\nfor study for Cuban children, will\nbe held, with selected speakers\npresiding.\nThis institution of learning is\nto he erected on the site on\nSmith\u2019s Lane, which was selected\nby the committee, and will thus\nbe adjacent to San Carlos theater\nand of easy access from the hall.\nThe school wiU face on Smith's\nLane, and will be about 100 feet\nfrom Duval street.\nFor this new and commodious\nbuilding for Cuban students, the\nNational Army of Cuba will fur\nnish the material and the work\nmen will be employed by the\nCuban government.\nFollowing the ceremonies, at\n10 o\u2019clock, pilgrimage will start to\nthe city cemetery where addresses\nWill be made and wreaths placed\non the Maine monument and the\nmonument erected in memory of\nthe Cubans who lost their lives in\ntheir country\u2019s battles for liberty.\nTo the Marti monument at Bay\nview Park the assemblage will\nmarch at 11 o\u2019clock, where\nwreaths will be placed and from\nthere to the monument to Con\nfederate Veterans, where other\nwreath* wiH be placed.\nSpeakers at these events will\ninclude Major J. D. Mac Mullen,\nU. S. A., commending officer at\nKey West barrack*, and Captain\nW, Curry Ilarris, Florida National\nGuard, commanding Battery *\u2018E\u201d.\nIn the afternoon at 3 o\u2019clock\nthere will be played a game of\nbaseball between the Cuban Naval\nAcademy team and a group of\nplayer* selected from the teams in\nKev West.\nAt night there will be held in\nFan Carlos hail a Velada, which\nwill, it is expected, be attended by\ntarge and representative number\nof Cuban and American citizens.\nTomorrow night a series of of\nficial act* will be carried out by.\nthe city and a punch will be of\nfered the distinguished visitor*.\nThere will be a dance given at\nCoral Isle Casino, and at the\nCuban Club, and a welcome will\nbe extended to the visitor*.\nDuring the day high official\nrepresentative* of the Cuban gov\nernment will make official visits\nthe civil and military authori\nties.\nMonday, all day will be devoted\nto shopping and sightseeing, and\non that day as well aa tomorrow\nand Sunday there will be baseball\n(Continued on Page Four)\nNEW ERA\nDANCE\nTanight. 9 till\nCUBAN CLUB\nPritchard's Orchestra\nAdmission Me Ladies Free\n\u2014Members Half Price\u2014\nTEXACO ROOFINGS AND ROOF COATINGS, PLASTICS, ETC. YOU NEED HaVE NO LEAKY ROOF IF YOU CONSULT SOUTH FLA. CONTR. AND ENG. CO.\nSlljc tKey Meat Citizen\nMrs. Lorimer Expresses\nGreat Delight With Her\nVisit To Island City\nMrs. W. L. Lorimer, of Camp\nRoosevelt at Perry-Cn\u2014The-Lake,\nOhio, is leaving this afternoon on\nthe S. S. Cuba for Tampa, after\nspending several days looking over\nconditions in Key West with a\nview to establishing a winter camp\nhere for boys.\nSeen this morning by The Citi\nzen, Mrs. Lorimer expressed her\nself as being delighted with her\nstay and the many attractive\nscenes she had seen and was par\nticularly pleased with the many\ncourtesies extended. Asked to\ngive an outline of her experiences,\niMrs. Lorimer said:\n\u201cI read in \u2018Traveler\u2019 an article\nby Harold S. Kahm, which began,\n\u2018lt was impossible for me to be\nlieve that I was in the United\nStates.\u2019 I\u2019m not going to say just\nthat, but I shall say that it seems\ntoo good to be true that in the\nbur.ry of the mode ih these Unit\ned States, that Key West offers\nsuch a pleasant surprise in friend\nliness and leisure.\n\u201cI have enjoyed to the fullest\nmy visit heTe. Mr. Singleton, of\nyour Chamber of Commerce, has\nbeen my host and through him I\nhave met and talked with many\nof your leading citizens, and each\nof them had a really pleasing way\nof making me feel that I wasn\u2019t\nany bother.\nHospitality Band Gives\nConcert At Fort Taylor\nBoys at the C. 0. C. Camp at\nFort Taylor were given a musical\ntreat yesterday afternoon when\nthe Key West Hospitality Band\nset down their sheet racks and\nproceeded to play a delightful\nconcert for the members of the j\ncamp and those in charge.\nBesides the campers there were\na number of guests and members\nof the Army colony present, and\ntheir enjoyment of the unexpect\nScout Troops To Join\nIn Cuban Celebration\nNEW CALL FOR\nBRIDGE WORKERS\nREQUISITIONS RECEIVED TO\nDAY FOR DIFFERENT\nOPERATIVES\ni _____\nv Among requisition* for labor\nf era on the bridges contracts was\nion\u00a9 this morning asking for four\nwhite laborers to be sent for\n[work on Contract H-3. near Low\n{er Matecumbe.\nThese men are to be sent to\nthe Oversews Rood and Toll Bridge\nContract, which is being supervis\ned by Captain Ed. Sheeran, and\nwill work on the bascule bridge,\nwhich is being sealed into the\ni rest of the bridge and become a\npart of the bridge proper,\nj Four rough carpenters and\neight negro laborer* are to be\n(cnt to Ooneh Key to be used by\nthe Y. Thomason Construction\nCompany on Contract B.\n\u201cI ate broiled crawfish at a\nvery clean' little restaurant, where\nthe proprietor and his wife were\nmost perfect host and hostess. It\nwag such a pleasant place for a\nstranger, and the food was so ex\ncellent that I have had other\ndinners there.\n\u201cI am staying at the La Con\ncha Hotel. It is the only hotel at\nwhich I ever stayeo that had an\nhonest and real friendliness all\nthe way through. \u201cIt is really a\npleasure to be here.\n\u201cOne day I visited the Keys and\nwent fishing. I had a most won\nderful time, and I was so agree\nably surprised at the roads, the\nbridges and the people living along\nthe way. I had thought of the\nother Florida Keys, that is other\nthan Key West, as being nothing\nbut desolate places.\n\u201cI have walked over, around\nand through Key West, from be\nginning to end. I\u2019ve rested along\nthe way and always found some\none willing to talk. I think I\nhave talked about everything ex\ncept the next presidential elec\ntion.\n\u201cThis afternoon I am return\ning to Tampa, having completed\nthe work I came here to do, but\nI truly hope to return in a short\ntime to make Key West my perm\nanent winter home.\u201d\ncd musical treat was evidenced\nby their applause and verbal ex\npression* of appreciation.\nI, .Fallowing the program the musi\ncians were invited to join the\nciwp members at a wholesome\nsupper served in the canteen, and\na very pleasant afternoon was\nenjoyed.\nIt was. stated this morning that\neach week the band will be heard\nin selected programs at the C. C.\nC. Camp.\nMembers of scout troops in\nKey West, both girl* and boys,\nare to take part in the exercises\nto be held October 10, in com\nmemoration of \u201cEl Grito de\nYara.\u201d\nThe scouts are requested to\nmeet Sunday morning 8:15 o\u2019clock\nin fult uniform and report to\nScoutmaster Victor Larsen, of\nTroop No. 52. AH those who\nhave their uniforms are par\nticularly urged to attend.\nThis invitation ha* been ex\ntended by representative* of the\nCuban government and it is ex\npected that response* will be evi\ndenced by a full attendance,\nCHANGES HIS NAME\nNEW YORK. Because be\nthought his name was a \u201cdrawback\nsocial*v and sounded un-Ameri\ncan,\u201d Hubert us Ralph Theodore\nRooseve t Kretzaghunaa of this\ncity bad it changed to Theodore\n1 Roosevelt.\nKEY WEST, FLORIDA, FRIDAY, OCTOBER 8, 1937.\nBuilding Permits Covering\nSeven Days Total $16,900\nBuilding permits issued from\nthe office of Building Inspector\nHarry M. Baker during the first\nseven days of October total $16,-\n900 as against the issues for Sep\ntember which totaled $6,375.\n(Of the $16,900 the permits is\nsued to Julian Marks came to\n$16,500 and were issued for work\nwhich Mr. Marks has started on,\nhis holdings at the eastern end of\nthe Island on the land recently j\npurchased by him and was known 1\nas the Biological Station.\nThree permits were issued the|\napplicant. One for a residence!\nECONOMIC HIGHLIGHTS\nHappenings That Affect the Dinner Pails, Dividend\nChecks and Tax Bills of Every Individual; Na\ntional and International Problems Insep\narable From Welfare\nTo put it mildly, the business\noutlook today is extremely con\nfused.\nOn the one hand, it is predicted\nthat this winter\u2019s domestic com\nmerce will he the best since 1929,\nwith retail sjfes in some lines per\nhaps exceeding the boom-time\nfigure. On the other, business\nleaders are seriously disturbed\u2014\nand many of them are plainly\npessimistic as to the trend ef fu\nture events.\nThi s anomaly is easily explain\ned. For, in the view of execu\ntives, the short-term outlook is\nfavorable, and the long-term out\nlook is bad. Purchasing power is\nup, farm income is at a six-year\nhigh, consumer goods are moving\nrapidly. Vet the unrest in Eu\nrope, the tangled political! situa\ntion at home, including the threat\nof more government in business,\nthe apparent certainty of higher\ntaxes, the prospect of still more\nserious labor disturbances,- and\nthe nervousness of security in\nvestors and speculators are re\ntarding factors.\nAs everyone knows, the stock\nmarket took it* biggest drop in\nyears a few Weeks ago. Values are\nfar below their spring and early\nsummer levels. And while the\nstock market is not necessarily\nan accurate barometer of actual\nbusiness conditions, it does pretty\na\u2019osely reflect the views of finance\non both big and small levels, and\nrepresent* credit, capital and re\nserve spending power. Explana\ntions of th drop varied, and dis\nclosed the opposed schools of\nthought now in existence. Stock\nmarket officials ascribed the cbl\nlapse as beinrr the mainly to ex\ncessively strict regulating by tho\nSEC, which h?s largrfy eliminated\nspeculative operators who in the\npa*t could be trusted to take up\nmuch of the slack in thin mar\nkets. Government officials, such\n|a s SEC head James Landis, who\nj has recently resigned to become\nDean of Law at Harvard, defend\ned the regulatory policy, intimat\ned that sill more stringent regula\ntion may be necessary. Whether\nthe Landis\u2019 point of view is right\nor wrong, such a policy evidently\nhas a dampening effect on large\nindustry.\nSo far a* the politic*! situation\n!is concerned, all is chaos. Presi\ndent Roosevelt\u2019s sweep around the\nciuntry, in the view of most com\nmentators, is designed to give him\nI a chance to meet see people, to\nI use his personality, and to enlist\nj public support in hi* campaign\ni against the conservative wing of\nI his party. The President, as he\nhas said in almost so many word*,\nis now envisioning a \u201csecond New\nI Peat\u201d which involves still far\nther enlarging Federal authority,\nnew and restrictive fiegisfatien\ndealing with business practices,\nnotably in the field of wages and\nhoars, and a lessening of the pow\ner of the Federal judiciary. There\n|ha still talk that a special session\nmay be called late this fall. And\nit is known that the AOministra\ntkn wil f present an ambitious and\ninclusive \"must\" program before\nthe second session of the 75th\nCongress. which convene* in Jan\nuary, including reintroduction of\na Supreme Court \u201cpacking\u201d bill.\nEvidence is not lacking that\n[Mr. Rooseveffs popular following\nhas diminished\u2014the Slack Khz\nKlux Rlaa disclosure* are perhaps\n(the nct serious Mow he ha* re\ni which Will be about 40 by 80 feet\nand will cost approximately $12,-\n000. One for a garage apartment\nto cost about $2,000 and the\nother for a boat house to cost\nj $2,500.\n\u25a0j Other issues are for:\n(general repairs to residence at\n;|903 Whitehead street. Owner,\ni(Mrs, G. H. Walker; cost, SIOO.\nj General repairs to residence on\nAnn street. Owner, Mrs. Milton\nCurry; cost, SSO. N\nj General repairs to residence at\nj Grinnell and Eaton streets. Own\ner, Archie Thompson; cost, $250.\nccivpd. But it cannot yet be said\nwith accuracy that a majority of\nthe voters are no longer willing\nto follow his lead.\nIn some quarters it appears that\nwar scares have been exaggerat\ned\u2014and in others they have been\ntoo much minimized. A major war\ncould not help but tremendously\naffect American industry, wheth\ner we became involved as bellig\nerents or not. General expert\nview is that there will be no war\nnext year\u2014but that there will be\none in 1939, when Europe\u2019s vast\nrearmament program is more or\nless completed. American foreign\npolicy has so far been careful, even\ntfrnfci\u2014a s it must. We are in the\ndelicate position of attempting to\nkeep clear of*war\u2014yet having to\nmaintain our prestige in the in\nterest of American citizens and\nresidents abroad. Hot-heads crit\nicize Secretary Hull for what they\nthink is vacillation. Cooler heads\ngenerally approve his policy, think\nthat he i s right in seeking to feel\nour way gentry and carefully.\nThere is talk of an entirely new\ngross earnings tax on business.\nThis, coming on top of the pres\nent corporation income tax, the\nprofits and loss levy, the surplus\ntax and other taxes, might make\nit impossible for business to main\ntain expected dividends, even in\na time of heavy orders. There is\nno organized movement behind\nsuch a tax, however. Business is\nworried about the general tax\npolicy, and about the continued\ngovernment deficit* which will re\nquire heavy new taxes of some\nkind\u2014unless an unlooked-for re\ntrenchment in government spend\ning occur*.\nIn conclusion, it should be point\ned out that some expert* feel\nI that the present business reces\nsion is less important than it\nseems, that the political and tax\nsituation will work out without\ndeing too much damage. Best\nguess is: The short-term outlook\nI for' commerce is favorable, and\n;the long-term outlook is in the\n1 laps of the gods.\nj According to Business Week of\nSeptember 18, a dollar of earning\nJ*>wer could be bought for $11.49\nat that time, as against $18.17 a\nyear before.\nSTEAMER OZARK\nARRIVES HERE\nSteamship Ozark, of th\u00a9 Clyde-\nMallory lines, arrived this morn\ning 9:60 o'clock from Jackson\nville and Miami, discharged cargo\nof which three carload* was lum\nber for local firm*, and sailed 2\no\u2019clock for New Orleans.\nSteamship Granada, of the\nStandard Fruit and Steamship\ncompany, is due tomorrow morn\ning 3:45 oVlick. will take bunk\ners nt the Porter Dock Company,\nand continue the trip to Froa\ntera, Mexico.\nPAUL REVERE RIDES AGAIN\nBOLYSTON, Mam. Charged\nwith confusing red and green\n%bts on a midnight rido. Pan!\nRevere \u00a9f this city eras arrested\nby Police Chief Richard Smith\nand given a traffife violation\nticket.\nYankees Take Third Straight\nGame By Score Of Five To One\nPlan Bringing Portable\nBuildings Here For Use\nAs Community Center\nSENATOR PEPPER\nGIVES ADDRESS\nONDEMOCRACY\n\nHEARD BY THREE THOUSAND\nDELEGATES TO NEW YORK\nHERALD TRIBUNE FORUM\n6N WORLD PROBLEMS\nNEW YORK, Oct 8 (FNS).\nAddressing a visible audience of\n3,000 delegates to the New York\nHerald Tribune Forum on World\ni Problems, his words carried to\nI countless listeners throughout the\nnation on a coast to coast hook-up,\nSenator Claude Pepper of Florida\nI spoke for the youth of the\nDemocratic party here this week\nappearing on the same program\nwith President Roosevelt, Mrs.\ni Roosevelt, Henry Wallace, J. Ed\ngar Hoover and many other not\nables.\n\u201cThe nation\u2019* youth,\u201d Senator\nj Pepper asserted, \u201cviews with a\ntough mind and even as stout a\nheart the battlfield of life in\nwhich youth know* but one direc\ntion\u2014forward.\nHis goal has perfective, too,\nfor rn a large vision he encom\ni passes not a few but many; he\n(sees not a few individuals who be\nilieve in economic cannibalism and\nI succor themselve R from the sub\nstace of others, but the social\nunit, a nation, so united and in\nterdependent in interest, as well\nas sympathy and affection, that\nthe general and common perspec\ntive which shall mark the general\nand common course be but the\ngeneral and common good; and\nwith a passion born of youth's in\ncomparable fervor he shall per\nsist in the counsel of that course,\nfor it satisfies his sense, not only\nof economic but 0* moral right.\u201d\nSenator Pepper\u2019s speech was\npronounced one of the best on\nI the foigjn program and he re\nceived many compliments follow\ning its delivery.\nFIGHT AGAINST\nTUBERCULOSIS\nBEING RENEWED\nREPORT ISSUED BY STATE\nBOARD OF HEALTH SHOWS\nLOSS FROM DISEASE DUR\nING LAST YEAR\nJACKSONVILLE, oct 8 (FNS).\n\u2014Figures released this week by\nthe State Board of Health esti\nmate that Florida\u2019* loss from\ntuberculosis last year was approx\nimately $10,000,009. This figure\nwas based on a state survey and\nupon figures made available by\nmajor insurance companies. Dr.\nj A. J. Logie, dimeter of the divi\nsion of taberrotseis. said.\nDr. Logie stated that the\n-date's anti-tuberculoai# program\nis in the proeeaa of beta* found\ned and in the bey-inning \u2022dll of\nnecessity be limited to high aebool\nchildren, contact* and suspected\ncase*. He stated, however, that\nhe hoped certain industrial croupe\nmight be added later.\n\"Industry,\u2019' he said, \u201cmost\nbecome aware of this major prob\nlem and safeguard its internet* by\ninsist mg upon the tuberculosa test\nand X-ray of its employes a* an\nintegral part of the tmtnmary ex\nam mat km\n\"Our eeanmonitka.** be reatrna\n\u2666d. \u201cmast realise that million* of]\ndollar* can be saved the state;\nif they will help bring totem\nieete under control.\"\nWill Be Means 01 Fill\ning Long-Felt Need Of\nMeeting Hall For Youth\nActivities\n\u2022Efforts are being continued to\nraise fund s for tbe purpose of\nbringing to Key West two build\ning* which are to be u*ed a* a\ncommunity center. These build\ning* are to be brought to this city\nfrom Jacksonville and used a* a\nmeeting place for organisations of\ngirls and boys.\nEach of the buildings are 20 by\n120 feet, and are built as are ail\nother CCG building*, easily taken\ndown, carried from one place to\nanother and just a* easily erect\ned. The site has been selected by\nthe city, and plans for transpor\ntation are being continued.\nMany citizens have expressed\nthe need for such building* and\nare very much in favor of such a\nprogram, which will give this city\na center which may be used for\npresenting plays, musical*, and\nother forms of entertainment.\nJoe Youngblood, of the NYA\nadministration, ha* written a let\nter to Key West, received yester\nday, in which it b urged that\nevery effort be made to secure\none or two of these buildings, bo\ncause they are very much needed\nin Key West.\nPAYS BP TAXES\nON HOTEL HERE\nDELINQUENCY AGAINST LA\nCONCHA PROPERTY WAS\n$3,249.40\nHenry Dew, receiver for the\nLa Concha Hotel interest* yes\nterday, while visiting briefly In\nKey West, made a payment of the\ndelinquent taxes due the city\nwhich totalled $3,249.40.\nTax Assessor-Collector Sam\nPtnder said that the approximate\nassessment on the total was $20,-\n000, which was paid on the 20\nper cent basis on which collections\nare now being made.\nPayment of the assessment was\nmade in bond* and cash, $1,104.30\nbeing in bonds, and $2,144.00 in\nrash, which Mr. Dew handed over\nwith a smile.\nMr. Dew then went to the\ncounty tax collector's office where\nlit was his intention to pay the\nhotel\u2019s county taxes, but this was\nnot accomplished as there are\nsome matters to be straightened\nout before the collector will ac\ncept the payment\nToday Tax Collector Frank H.\nLadd was asked the states of the\nmatter, and said that he Is today\nwriting Comptroller i. M. Lor, at\nTaflahaesee. for certain tafermn\nt*on relative to these taxes and\nexpects to receive a reply within\nthe next week.\nRATED FIRST FAMILY\nOWOSSO, Mich.\u2014The Shstturk\nfamily of this city Is rated thei\n\u201cfirst'* family because they!\nbrought to this city the first!\nsewing machine, cabinet organ,\ntore projector, autom ofeile, radio\nMrpteflo-\nKey West, Florida, has the\nmost equable climate in the\ncountry; with an average\nrange of only 14* Fahrenheit\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nSchumacher And Pearson,\nRight Handers, Were\nStart-Off Pitchers In\nToday\u2019s Game\nspecial to Tke CHlhs)\nPOLO GROUNDS, Oct. B.\nBruised and battered, New York\nGiants came to their home grounds\ntoday after being twice defeated\nby the Yankees at tha Yankee\nStadium, in the hope tiiat the\ntide would turn in their favor, but\nit was a forlorn hope as the Yanks\nagain emerged the winners, this\ntime, S to 1.\nMonte Pearson pitched airtight\nball for the first four innings, al\nlowing no hits and giving no\nl\nbase* on halts, but in the last\nframe, after two were out, he\nweakened by allowing Isis first\nbase on balls, following it up wit||\nanother pass, filling the base*.\nThe* Murphy relieved him.\nAfter tke first inning Schu\nmacher was hit ceasisteatly for\nthe next five innings, and got out\nof bh4 aq\u2014\u2014,\nYankee power, class sad spirit\nseems to be too much el a handi\ncap for tha Giants to overcome,\nand temarraw\u2019s game at Polo\nGrourdt may he tke last of the\nseries.\nScor by innings] R. M. E.\nYankees 012 110 009\u2014 0 0\nGiants 000 000 100\u2014 1 8 3\nBatteries: Peer sen, Murphy and\nDickey; Schumacher, Brennan and\nDanntng..\nSummary of the contest fol\nlows:\nIn the first inning of the third\ngame of the 1937 World\u2019s Series,\nSchumacher started by walking\nCrosetti, then made a wild pitch,\nbut held the Giants scoreless and\nhitless, and distinguished himself\nby striking out DiMaggio. In the\nGiants\u2019 half, Pearson disposed of\nthe opposition la quick order.\nThe Yankees got the first run\nof the game, for a change, on a\ncouple of bits, in the second In\nning, and had the bases filled when\nRolfe fouled Out to retire the side.\nThe Giants were retired again in\nrotation.\nTwo runs were added by the\nYankees in the third inning, on s\nsingle by Gehrig and a triple by\nDickey, but the Giant# were stio\nunable to connect with Pearson's\ndeliveries and went out In quick\norder.\nAnother tally was secured by\nthe Yankees hi the fourth, but\nthe National Leaguers were help\nlew against the masterful pitch\nin* of Monte Pearson, who hod\nallowed no hit* in the four In\nning* played, and gnve no hns#\non bull*.\nThree errors and a sing**\nnetted the American Leaguers\nanother run in the fifth Inning.\nMcCarthy made two errors In try\ning to get one man In thew\nhalf the Giants finally broke the\nfce and Odessa got the first hit\nby beating out a blow U the in\nfield. but H was futile.\nRolf#, the first butter up m the\nsixth, hit lHs second tws lugger\nbut was mareswed as neither Geh\nrig nor Dickey reed advance him.\nJn the G*at*\u2019 half. Maore shifted\nICmtisuM sat Pag* Three\nTEN WIN\nDANCE\n(True By Isi\u00dfaSfcs)\nHABANAMADRID CLUB\nTeaseesww Night\n\u2014JOIN IN THE run\u2014","height":"24660","width":"19218"}}
